==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an older form ''heorot'', from Germanic ''*herut-'', from Indo-European ''*kerud-'' (Greek [[κορυδος]] ‘crested lark’), from ''*ker-, *kerə-'' (Latin [[cervus]] ‘horn’).  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[hirot]] (Dutch [[hert]]), Old High German [[hirz]] (German [[Hirsch]] ‘deer’), Old Norse [[hjǫrtr]] (Swedish [[hjort]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /heort/

===Noun===
'''heort''' ''m''
# a [[hart]] or [[stag]]

